@node "About EasyFR" "EasyFR.guide/About EasyFR"
@next "How to install"
@prev "Copyright"
@{b} About EasyFR@{ub}

 `EasyFR' projcet is born from my friend  Angelo  Vizzarro,  who  made  the
 first version of this software:
 "The idea of EasyFR  comes  in  my  mind  one  day  when  my  friend  Gino
 Casavecchia shows me some utility to handle File-Requests: I did like none
 of them. So, considering I was looking for a project to try using  MUI,  i
 started programming, and this is the result!"
 Unfortunatly Angelo Vizzarro stopped the project, due to lack of  time.  I
 asked  him  souce  codes, say I would be very happy to keep on developping
 this software. In this way we get to `EasyFR 2.0'.
 This is version 2.2, the second update that feature some small bug fix and
 some interesting news.

 `EasyFR' is an utility to help and handle File-Requests in an easyer way.

 Considering this, you will need to have:

 - an Amiga :-)
 - a modem
 - a Point
 - a mailer

 If you do not have these, probably you are not interested in EasyFR.

 EasyFR needs:

 - Kickstart 2.0 (you will need at least 2.1 to run localization)
 - MUI 3.x or newer installed (should work fine with 2.x too)
 - xpkmaster.library 2.4
 - traplist.library 5.2 (or later)

 These are some of the features:

 - Create and handle .REQ files to be sent to the BBS (with a mailer)  that
   should reply your request

 - Read and select directly from a fidonet box (a Filelist) files you  want
   to request; selected entries will be copied in the .REQ file

 - Backup of the .REQ file

 - Handle fidonet box (Filelist) packed with any XPK library

 - Find Next & Find Previous with progress indicator functions  in  fidonet
   boxes

 - Display info about nodes in nodelist (using traplist.library)

 - QuickList with most frequently used nodes

 - Run the mailer directly from EasyFR by pressing one button

 - Simple management of InBound: directory

 - List and extract LhA & LZX archives

 - EasyFR can associate a Filelist to a specific node (via traplist.library):
   changing node will change filelist too

 - GUI can be modified by the user,  this  thanx  Stefan  Stunz  and  his
   `@{"MagicĀUserĀInterface" link "Magic User Interface" 0}';

 - EasyFR takes advantages from using MUI 3.x. Bubble Help is available and
   can be disabled from registered users;

 - Localization: english, french, dutch and italian are distributed;

 - On-line help: pressing the HELP key, the AmigaGuide« help will be shown.
   Help is context-sensitive;

 As you can read, there is nothing really particular, but there seems  that
 other programs miss something.
 Some can run TrapDoor, do not handle fido boxes (Filelists), others do not
 support  traplist.library,  and  I  haven't  seen  any  one supporting XPK
 libraries.

 `EasyFR' try to handle File Requests in a complete and easy way.
@endnode

@node "Magic User Interface" "EasyFR.guide/Magic User Interface"

 `EasyFR' has been developed using `MUI' v3.3 ((C) Stefan Stunz).

 This mean:
 1) You MUST have `MUI' installed in order to run this program;
 2) You MUST have at least AmigaOS 2.04 (v37.175) in order to install `MUI'

 If you do not know `MUI', probably you won't be happy to loose some  space
 of your HD installing this package.

 I think you will change your opinion!

 `MUI' offers many feature to both the user and the programmer.

 Some examples:

 - A GUI following the Comodore's User Interface Style Guide;

 - Every `MUI' application can be iconified;

 - You can use the keyboard, instead of the 'usual' mouse;

 - Almost all elements will  automatically  fit  to  the  window  size  (if
   resiable) and to the selected font (witch may change);

 - Many GUI parameters (font, color, pattern,  background  images,  screen,
   etc.) can be changed directly from the user, using the @{"MUI-Prefs" link "MUI-Prefs" 0} program
   supplied with the distribution;

 I could go on, but i prefer to stop here (please, download `MUI' from your
 local  BBS  and  read the documentation); I only add that not having `MUI'
 installed means not to use all those programs that require  it  (and  they
 are more and more), not only `EasyFR'!
@endnode

@node "How to install" "EasyFR.guide/How to install"
@next "Let's go!"
@prev "About EasyFR"
@{b} How to install@{ub}

 1) Install @{"MUI" link "Magic User Interface" 0} in your sistem. `EasyFR' does not work without `MUI'

 2) Choose a dir and copy these files:
    - EasyFR            (executable)
    - EasyFR.info       (executable icon)
    - EasyFR.sleep.info (AppIcon for EasyFR)
    - EasyFR.guide      (on-line help)

 3) Create a dir named "C" and copy in it the file C/mouse2 provided with
    the distribution.

 4) EasyFR need his directory to be assigned as EasyFR:. Please do this and
    add it to the file s:user-startup.

 5) Copy the catalog file of your language (if provided) in the dir
    Locale:Catalogs/Italiano. Please note that locale support comes from
    Workbench 2.1 and later. If you are using WB 2.0, EasyFR will speak in
    English.

 For a full working it is  raccomanded  to  install  TrapDoor  package  (or
 another  mailer), and/or at least the traplist.library: `EasyFR' uses this
 library to handle node informations.

 Now installation is done.

 By the way you can install EasyFR using the installer script provided with
 the distribution... :-)

 EasyFR can be run either from a shell or  from  Workbench  double-clicking
 its icon. If you run EasyFR from shell, you can pass the  node  number  to
 use and the filelist.

 First of all, you need to configure the program with this parameters:

 - The command to run the mailer and make the call;
 - InBound directory path;
 - OutBound directory path;
 - Nodelist directory path;
 - Work dir path;

 For further information, please look at the @{"ConfigurationĀpage" link "Config Page" 0} or to @{"Let's" link "Let's go!" 0}
@{"Āgo" link "Let's go!" 0} page.

 Note: `EasyFR' help is context-sensitive. You only  have  to  mouse  mouse
 pointer over a gadged and press the help key. AmigaGuide« Help will be run
 automatically displaying information on the gadged.
@endnode

@node "Let's go!" "EasyFR.guide/Let's go!"
@next "Node to poll"
@prev "How to install"
@{b} Let's go!@{ub}

 EasyFR 2.2. can be run from both workbench and shell. If run  from  shell,
 EasyFR will use the ReadArgs() function to parse the arguments:

 FQFA/K,FILELIST

 The first argument must be a full qualified  fidonet  address,  while  the
 filelist is a filename with path. You cannot specify  a  filelist  without
 telling EasyFR which address you are talking about.

 At its first  run  `EasyFR'  need  to  be  configured.  Many  informations
 required  in  the first version are no more needed, because of the support
 of the traplist.library.

 After filling in the requested information in the configuration panel, the
 program is readi to run.

 The application is divided in 4 `pages':

 @{"MainĀPage" link "Main Page" 0}
 @{"NodelistĀPage" link "Nodelist Page" 0}
 @{"InBoundĀPage" link "InBoud Page" 0}
 @{"ConfigĀPage" link "Config Page" 0}

 New MUI users should know that almost  all  gadgets  of  the  GUI  can  be
 selected using the keyboard. You can move from one gadget to another using
 the TAB key (or SHIFT+TAB to move back).

 BTW, you can select the 4 pages of `EasyFR' using function keys F1, F2, F3
 e F4.

 Bacause of MUI, EasyFR 2  support  also  some  @{"ARexxĀĀcommand" link "ARexx" 0},   standard
 commands  provided  by  MUI itself. Further command will be implemented in
 later releases. The ARexx port name is `EASYFR'.
@endnode

@node "MUI-Prefs" "EasyFR.guide/MUI-Prefs"
@next "Main Page"
@prev "Let's go!"
@{b} MUI-Prefs@{ub}

 MUI registered users may change the look of EasyFR GUI.  Please  refer  to
 MUI documentation on how to use MUI-Prefs program.
@endnode

@node "Main Page" "EasyFR.guide/Main Page"
@next "Node to poll"
@prev "MUI-Prefs"
 @{b}Main Page@{ub}

 In this page you will find:

 - a section with the info about the @{"requestĀnode" link "Node to poll" 0};
 - a section with the @{"reqĀfileĀlist" link "File .REQ" 0};
 - a section with the @{"FileList" link "FileLists" 0}.
@endnode

@node "Node to poll" "EasyFR.guide/Node to Poll"
@next "File .REQ"
@prev "Main Page"
@{b} Request Node Address.@{ub}

 In the string-gadget you have to insert the address of the node  you  want
 to  call.  This  address must be a standard 4 dimension Fido-like address:
 something like x:yyy/zzz.p (zone:host/node.point).

 The address shall be present in  nodelist.  The  program  will  pop  up  a
 requester if the traplist.library can not find the node in the nodelist.

 For further info about the nodelist, please read @{"GlobalĀNodelist" link "Global Nodelist" 0}.

 Beside the string-gadget you will find a popup gadget; it will make appear
 a  small  list  view  where you will find the addresses you are using more
 often: this is the @{"QuickList" link "QuickList" 0}.

 Once  you  have  selected  a  valid  address,  node  information  will  be
 displayed. These informations are taken directly from the nodelist.

 If configured in this way, EasyFR will also look for the  filelist  linked
 with  the node (if exist): it will be read together with the .REQ file (if
 exist) of the node.
@endnode

@node "File .REQ" "EasyFR.guide/File .REQ"
@next "FileLists"
@prev "Node to poll"
@{b} Requested file-list (.REQ)@{ub}

 This area displays informations about files you want to request.


 The listview

 This listview displays the file names of the packages you want to  request
 (the  contents  of  the  .REQ).  File  names  can  be  added  directly  or
 double-clicking the filename from the filelist.


 The Add button

 To add directly the name of one file, simply press the  `Add'  button  and
 write the  name in the string gadget (that will  be  activated).  Pressing
 the return key the name will be inserted in the  listview.  You  can  also
 select a name from the @{"loadedĀĀfilelist" link "FileLists" 0}:  look  for  it  in  the  filelist
 listview, double-click it and it will be automatically inserted in the req
 listview.


 The Edit button

 By using thi sbutton you can edit a filename already inserted in the  file
 request list. You only have to select an entry and press the Edit  button:
 now  you can modify the string. Press return to finish.


 The Remove button

 To remove a single name from the list, simply select  an  entry  and  then
 press the Remove button.


 The Delete All button

 Using the `Delete all' button you will clear the .REQ list, cancelling the
 request.


 Auto-search checkmark

 The auto-serch checkmark tells the  program  to  look  for  the  name  you
 selected  in  the  Filelist.  This  could be handy if you want to know the
 lenght and/or the date of the program you are requestin.
@endnode

@node "FileLists" "EasyFR.guide/Filelist"
@next "Nodelist Page"
@prev "File .REQ"
@{b} File List for Request@{ub}

 This listview contains loaded Filelist, i.e. those  text  files  with  the
 list  of available files on a certain BBS. From this list you will be able
 to select with your mouse (or keyboard) those files you want  to  download
 from the BBS.

 `EasyFR 2' supports XPK libraries. Filelist are  text  files  and  can  be
 compressed  with  a  retio  >  50%.  Speed slow down stricly depend on the
 compression method you are using. Using a really fast unpacking packer can
 be faster than usgin plain filelist.
 The plain filelist loader has been completly  rewritten  and  now  is  60%
 faster than the old version.
 Unregistered users will find the xpk loader very slow.  This  because  the
 xpk loader is only for demo purpose in the evaluation version. If you like
 xpk libraries (like I do), please register.

 EasyFR offer to the feature of "linking" a filelist to  a  node:  in  this
 way,  every  time  you  select  the  node,  the  linked  filelist  will be
 automatically loaded. This information is  saved  in  the  extra  database
 handled  by  the traplist.library. BTW, you can also turn this feature off
 from the configuration panel.

 The name (and the path) of the filelist can be  inserted  direcly  in  the
 string  gadget  or  selected  via  the  popup,  that  will activate an ASL
 file-requester.

 You will also find an easy to use string search funtion.
@endnode

@node "Nodelist Page" "EasyFR.guide/Nodelist Page"
@next "Global Nodelist"
@prev "FileLists"
 @{b}Nodelist Page@{ub}

 In this page you will find:

 - @{"InformationĀonĀnodes" link "Global Nodelist" 0};
 - @{"TheĀQuicklist" link "QuickList" 0}.
@endnode

@node "Global Nodelist" "EasyFR.guide/Global Nodelist"
@next "QuickList"
@prev "Nodelist Page"
 @{b}Global Nodelist@{ub}

 From version 2.0,  EasyFR  uses  traplist.library  written  by  Maximilian
 Hantsch  and  Martin  Laubach.  In this way there is no more need to use a
 self made handling of the nodelist (as in  the  Ķpreviuos  release).  This
 make EasyFR more standard...

 Every information about nodes are completely handled by this library.  You
 have  not  to load big nodelist and to process them: traplist.library uses
 an index to speed up searching trough the nodelist itself.

 In the bottom you'll find a string gadged labeled `Node address': here you
 shall  write  the fidonet node number you want to look at. If this address
 exist, EasyFR will show every information available for this node.

 Displayed nodes can be added to the  @{"Quicklist" link "QuickList" 0} for a faster use.
@endnode

@node "QuickList" "EasyFR.guide/QuickList"
@next "InBoud Page"
@prev "Global Nodelist"
@{b} The QuickList@{ub}

 This is where you should add the most used  systems.  This  list  will  be
 shown every time you will activate the pop-up near the node address un the
 main page, where, double-clicking on a node, will select it.

 Please, have a look to @{"NodeĀtoĀpoll" link "Node to poll" 0}.

 `Add' and `Remove' buttons are used to add or  remove  the  node  that  is
 currently displayed to the QuickList.
 If you are using MUI 3, you can sort the nodes in the quicklist  via  drag
 and drop.

 Double-clicking an entry from this list will let EasyFR  display  informa-
 tions about it.
@endnode

@node "InBoud Page" "EasyFR.guide/InBound Page"
@next "InBound list"
@prev "QuickList"
 @{b}InBound Page@{ub}

 From this page you can perform some easy function of the InBound
 directory before and after the request. You can:
 - have a look to the @{"InBoundĀList" link "InBound list" 0},
 - perform some @{"commandsĀonĀfiles" link "InBound commands" 0}.
@endnode

@node "InBound list" "EasyFR.guide/InBound Directory list"
@next "InBound commands"
@prev "InBoud Page"
@{b} InBound directory List.@{ub}

 This page can be usefull before and after the  download  to  verify  witch
 files  are  present  and  witch  are  just arrived. Name, lenght, date and
 comment are displayed.

 Have a look to @{"InBoundĀcommands" link "InBound commands" 0}
@endnode

@node "InBound commands" "EasyFR.guide/InBound Commands"
@next "Config Page"
@prev "InBound list"
 @{b}InBound commands@{ub}

 @{u}Rescan InBound@{uu}

 Force EasyFR to read InBound directory again, usable after a download.


 @{u}Set Comment@{uu}

 This button let you edit the filenote of a file; this can be handy after a
 download when filenotes do not describe the contents of the file.
  

 @{u}Arc List@{uu}

 Open a console window and displays the contents of the selected file if it
 is  an  LhA or LZX archive. This feature runs the command you have inseted
 in the appropriate string gadget in the config page.
  

 @{u}Arc Extract@{uu}

 Extract the selected archive using the command in the  appropriate  string
 gadget in the config page.
  
  
 @{u}Sort by ...@{uu}

 From here you can select the sort method of the directory list, either  by
 Name or by Size or by Lenght.
@endnode

@node "Config Page" "EasyFR.guide/Config Page"
@next "Download command"
@prev "InBound commands"
 @{b}Config Page@{ub}

 This page contains all information  required  from  the  program  to  work
 properly. Following entries are requested:

 - @{"DownloadĀcommand" link "Download command" 0};
 - @{"ArcĀsettings" link "LhA list command" 0};

 - @{"InBoundĀpath" link "InBound Path" 0};
 - @{"OutBoundĀpath" link "OutBound Path" 0};
 - @{"NodelistĀpath" link "Nodelist Path" 0};
 - @{"WorkĀpath" link "Work Path" 0};

 Then you can choice to either to use the traplist.library or not to @{"linkĀa" link "Node-Filelist" 0}
@{"ĀFilelist" link "Node-Filelist" 0}  to a specific node address. On the right some information abount
 the registration status and the @{"XPKĀlibraries" link "XPK libraries" 0} status are displaied.
 Registered users may also enable the @{"backup" link "Backup" 0} for the .REQ file.  With  this
 option  on  you can use the "Add Backup" entry from the menu and the "Scan
 Inbound" button in the main page.

 Registered user using MUI 3 will be able to disable the @{"BubbleĀHelp" link "Bubble Help" 0}  using
 the switch just under the backup one.
@endnode

@node "Download command" "EasyFR.guide/Download Command"
@next "LhA list command"
@prev "Config Page"
@{b} Download command@{ub}

 `EasyFR' allow you to  directly  do  a  download  without  having  to  run
 manually  a  mailer  and  make  it  do  the  call. Anyway it cannot handle
 directly the modem. `EasyFR' will run the command you will enter  in  this
 string gadged every time you will push the call button in the main page.

 If you are using Trapdoor as mailer, you will  have  to  insert  something
 somilar  to the following line (let's suppose Trapdoor is in the directory
 Mail:bin/):

    Mail:bin/Trapdoor CALL %a

 The tocken %a will be sobstituted with the current address. You are
 supposed to use a mailer that support traplist.library too, because no
 telephone number is inserted (future release may support this, too).

 For further information about Trapdoor or other mailer,  please  refer  to
 theri documentation.
@endnode

@node "Archive config" "EasyFR.guide/Archive confoguration"
@next "InBound Path"
@prev "Download command"
@{b} Archive configuration@{ub}

 In this section you find a register frame to select the archiver you  want
 to  configure, and two string gadgets where to insert the list and extract
 commands.


 @{u}List archive command@{uu}

 Here you must insert the command that will be  executed  on  the  selected
 file  in  the  InBound  listview when you press the `Arc List' button. The
 command should look like:

     C:Lha l -Qa %f

 where %f is the filename of the selected entry.  There  is  non  need  the
 specify   the   redirection   on  a  console:  a  window  will  be  opened
 automatically.


 @{u}Arc extract command@{uu}

 Here you must insert the command that will be  executed  on  the  selected
 file  in the InBound listview when you press the `Arc Extract' button. The
 command should look like:

     C:Lha x -Qa %f RAM:

 where %f is the filename of the selected entry.  There  is  non  need  the
 specify   the   redirection   on  a  console:  a  window  will  be  opened
 automatically.
@endnode

@node "InBound Path" "EasyFR.guide/InBound Path"
@next "OutBound Path"
@prev "Archive config"
@{b} InBoud path@{ub}

 Insert here the  full  path  of  the  directory  where  your  mailer  puts
 downloaded   files.  This  path  shall  be  the  same  as  in  the  mailer
 configuration file.

 Examples: Mail:InBound/
           InBound:
@endnode

@node "OutBound Path" "EasyFR.guide/OutBound Path"
@next "Nodelist Path"
@prev "InBound Path"
@{b} OutBoud path@{ub}

 Insert here the full path of the directory where you want .REQ file saved.
 This one should be the same directory where mail packet are saved from the
 tosser. This path shall be the same as in the mailer configuration file.

 Examples: Mail:OutBound/
           OutBound:
@endnode

@node "Nodelist Path" "EasyFR.guide/Nodelist Path"
@next "Work Path"
@prev "OutBound Path"
@{b} Nodelist path@{ub}

 Insert here the full path of the nodelist directory. This  path  shall  be
 the same as in the Traplist configuration file.

 Examples: Mail:Nodelist/
           Nodelist:
@endnode

@node "Work Path" "EasyFR.guide/Work path"
@next "Node-Filelist"
@prev "Nodelist Path"
@{b} Work path@{ub}

 `EasyFR' needs a work directory where to write  some  temp  files.  Insert
 here  the  full  path  of this directory. Usually it is better to select a
 path in the Ram Disk, but you can select a path on you hard drive too.

 Examples: T:
           Ram:T/
@endnode

@node "Node-Filelist" "EasyFR.guide/Node-Filelist link"
@next "Backup"
@prev "Work Path"
@{b} Filelist link@{ub}

 Using three radio buttons you can select the behaviour of the program when
 you change the node of the system you want to request to.

 @{u}Clear at node change@{uu}
 every time you select a new node in the main window, the filelist listview
 is cleared.

 @{u}Take the same@{uu}
 the contents of the listview is kept even when you change  node.  You  can
 still load a new filelist.

 @{u}Node Association@{uu}
 the program remember the last Filelist used for a specific node, and  load
 it when that node is selected.
 Filelist path and name are recorded in the extra database handled  by  the
 traplist.library.  This  function  is  available  only  if this library is
 installed.
@endnode

@node "Backup" "EasyFR.guide/.REQ file Backup"
@next "Bubble Help"
@prev "Node-Filelist"
 @{b}.REQ file backup@{ub}

 This checkmark enable the backup of the .REQ file. WHen this  function  is
 on,  you  will  be  able  to use the "@{"ScanĀInbound" link "File .REQ" 0}" function from the main
 panel, and the "Append Backup" from the menu.

 This function is only available for registered users.
@endnode

@node "Bubble Help" "EasyFR.guide/Bubble Help"
@next "XPK libraries"
@prev "Backup"
 @{b}Bubble Help@{ub}

 If you are using MUI 3.x, EasyFR will enable the  Bubble  Help.  Bubble
 Help localization is done via a separate catalog. If you do not install
 both catalogs, you could use EasyFR with a different languages, one for
 the program and one for the Bubble Help.
@endnode

@node "XPK libraries" "EasyFR.guide/XPK Libraries"
@next "ARexx"
@prev "Bubble Help"
@{b} XPK Libraries@{ub}

 XPK is an interface standard between programs and packer libraries.  Every
 XPK application can handle datas packed with every XPK packer library: you
 only need that specific packer library and also `EasyFR 2.x' will be  able
 to read packed Filelist.

 XPK  libraries  are  distributed  in  two  archives   `xpkXXusr.lha'   and
 `xpkXXdev.lha',  where  XX  is  the  version number. Currently distributed
 version is 2.5. You can find them from your local  BBS  or  on  an  Aminet
 mirror.

 Thanx goes to:
 
  Urban Dominik Mueller    umueller@amiga.physik.unizh.ch
  Bryan Ford               bryanf@hpmcaa.mcm.hp.com
  Peter Struijk            ddws0168@dutiws.tudelft.nl
  Christian von Roques     roques@karlsruhe.gmd.de
  Andre Beck               beck@freia.inf.tu-dresden.de
  Marc Zimmermann          zimmerma@ibr.cs.tu-bs.de
  Kristian Nielsen         bombadil@diku.dk
  Torsten Juergeleit       bj030@aix370.rrz.uni-koeln.de
  Matthias Scheler         tron@uni-paderborn.de
  Uwe Roehm                roehm@kirk.fmi.uni-passau.de
  Martin A. Blatter        blatter@amiga.physik.unizh.ch

 ...and may others.

 EasyFR  2.0  support  XPK  libraries.  You  only  need  to   install   the
 xpk25usr.lha package (where 25 is the version number) to make `EasyFR 2.0'
 to read XPK packed filelist. There are many  other  packer  libraries  not
 dostributed with the original archive. You can find the on may BBSes or on
 internet.

 Filelist are text files and can be packed with a ratio  up  to  60-70%.  I
 suggest   you   to  try  to  pack  filelist  with  the  NUKE  method  (the
 xpknuke.library can be found in the original XPK archive): using this  one
 you will gain more than 60% on text file keeping hi-speed decompression.

 @{b}WARNING@{ub}: registered users will make use of an optimized (either in time or
 in  space)  finction  for reading packed filelist. @{i}Unregistered users@{ui} will
 note a slow down and will need more memory for read them.  I  suggest  you
 not to read big packed filelist, or you will have to wait long time.
 On my A2000/030 (25 Mhz), `EasyFR  2.0',  020+  registered  version,  took
 about  14  seconds  to  read  a packed Aminet INDEX filelist (Uncompressed
 length 1119741 bytes, Compressed length 443256 bytes) loading it from HD.
@endnode

@node "ARexx" "EasyFR.guide/ARexx"
@next "How to register"
@prev "XPK libraries"
@{b} ARexx Interface@{ub}

 EasyFR 2.x have the standard ARexx interface provided by MUI (quit,  hide,
 deactivate,   show,  activate,  info,  help):  please  refer  to  the  MUI
 documentation for further information about these commands. Other commands
 will  be  implemented  in  next  releases,  to make it possible to program
 `EasyFR' with an ARexx script.
@endnode

@node "How to register" "EasyFR.guide/Come registrarsi"
@next "Author address"
@prev "XPK libraries"
@{b} How to register@{ub}

 From release 2.0, EasyFR is become shareware. You can use  EasyFR  for  an
 evaluation  period  of  3 weeks. After this period, if you like it, if you
 think it is useful and it is a well done program, you  have  to  register.
 The  registration  fee  can  be  payed in italian lire (15.000  lire),  in
 american dollars (10 US $) german marks (15 DM).
 When possible, postal money order should  be  payble  at  the  Turin  Post
 Office number 27.

 If you are a shareware programmer, you can exchange a registered  copy  of
 your program with EasyFR.key. Please, mail me for further information  and
 agreements.

 To register fill in the @{"RegistrationĀform" alink "Registration.form/main" 0} and send it to  the  @{"author" link "Author address" 0}  via
 snail mail or via e-mail.
 If you want to receive your keyfile via e-mail, you must send me your  PGP
 public key, otherwise I will send you the key via standard mail.

 Remember that future developing of this software depend on your support.
@endnode

@node "Author address" "EasyFR.guide/Come contattare l'autore"
@next "History"
@prev "How to register"
